<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">23981903</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2014</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>02</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2022</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>08</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1873-6815</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>48</Volume><Issue>11</Issue><PubDate><Year>2013</Year><Month>Nov</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Experimental gerontology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Exp Gerontol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Interleukin-6 -174G/C gene polymorphism affects muscle damage response to acute eccentric resistance exercise in elderly obese women.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1255</StartPage><EndPage>1259</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1255-9</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.exger.2013.08.009</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0531-5565(13)00272-6</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>The IL-6 gene polymorphism has been associated with disease prevalence and different physiological responses to exercise. Eccentric resistance exercise (ERE) is considered a nonpharmacological tool to prevent the chronic degenerative profile associated with aging and obesity. Consequently, the aim of the present study was to investigate the influence of IL-6 -174G/C polymorphism on acute interleukin-6 (IL-6) and creatine kinase (CK) temporal response to ERE in elderly obese women. Ninety women completed seven sets of ten repetitions (eccentric only) of an acute ERE session at 110% of the ten repetitions maximum (10RM). IL-6 genotypes displayed no difference at baseline. ERE induced changes in CK concentration over time occurred only in the GG group, F(2.619, 136.173)=5.199, p=0.003, with CK activity increased from 106.8&#xb1;6.9 U/l pre-intervention to 122.7&#xb1;11.2 U/l at 24 h and 131.9&#xb1;14.4 U/l at 48 h post-exercise. IL-6 concentration in the GG group was lower than the CC/CG group only at 0 h post-exercise (3.78&#xb1;0.58 pg/ml versus 6.51&#xb1;1.91 pg/ml, p=0.030). Only the GG genotype group had higher CK activity 24-48 h following ERE and greater CK integral values, while IL-6 activity over 48 h was higher in the CC/CG genotype group. In conclusion, IL-6 genotype affects CK and IL-6 in response to ERE. It is of interest that the ERE protocol induced an elevation in CK, indicating possible muscle damage without exacerbating IL-6 and CK for the GG genotype.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2013.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Funghetto</LastName><ForeName>Silvana Schwerz</ForeName><Initials>SS</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of Brasilia, Graduation Program in Health Sciences, Brasilia, Brazil. Electronic address: silvana.funghetto@gmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Prestes</LastName><ForeName>Jonato</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Silva</LastName><ForeName>Alessandro de Oliveira</ForeName><Initials>Ade O</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Farias</LastName><ForeName>Darlan L</ForeName><Initials>DL</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Teixeira</LastName><ForeName>Tatiane G</ForeName><Initials>TG</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Vieira</LastName><ForeName>Denis Cesar Leite</ForeName><Initials>DC</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Souza</LastName><ForeName>Vin&#xed;cius C</ForeName><Initials>VC</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Sousa</LastName><ForeName>Nuno M F</ForeName><Initials>NM</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Navalta</LastName><ForeName>James W</ForeName><Initials>JW</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Melo</LastName><ForeName>Gislane F</ForeName><Initials>GF</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Karnikowski</L